  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When a buyer at your open home says they are pre-approved and ready to move quickly, it sounds reassuring. But pre-approval and formal loan approval are not the same thing, and understanding the difference matters a great deal when you are deciding which offer to accept, whether to grant a finance extension, or how to manage the period between signing and settlement.</p>

      <p>This is not a reason to distrust buyers who come with pre-approval. Most finance campaigns go through without issue. But as a seller, knowing how the approval process actually works gives you better information to make decisions during what can be a pressured negotiation period.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What pre-approval actually means</h2>
      <p>A pre-approval, sometimes called conditional approval or approval in principle, is a lender's assessment that a borrower is likely to qualify for a loan up to a certain amount. It is based on information the borrower provides at the time of application: income, employment status, existing debts, and a credit check. The lender has assessed the borrower's financial position and said, in effect, that they would be willing to lend subject to finding a suitable property and completing a full assessment.</p>

      <p>The critical word is conditional. Pre-approval is not a guarantee of funding. The lender has not yet assessed the specific property being purchased, and they have not completed the full credit and serviceability checks that formal approval requires. Changes in the borrower's circumstances since pre-approval was granted can also affect the outcome. A job change, a new debt, or a significant change in interest rates can all alter what a lender is willing to approve when the full application is submitted.</p>

      <p>Pre-approvals also expire. Most last 90 days, though some lenders issue shorter ones. A buyer with a pre-approval granted four months ago may be working from an assessment that no longer reflects current lending conditions.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The difference between pre-approval and formal approval</h2>
      <p>Formal approval, sometimes called unconditional approval, is issued after the lender has assessed both the borrower and the specific property being purchased. At this stage, the lender has ordered a valuation of the property, confirmed that it meets their lending criteria, and completed all remaining checks on the borrower's financial position. When a buyer has formal approval, the bank has committed to lending the money for that specific property at that price.</p>

      <p>The gap between pre-approval and formal approval is where most finance-related difficulties occur. Lenders occasionally value properties below the purchase price, particularly in a rising market where comparable sales are lagging actual buyer sentiment. If the bank values your property at less than the agreed purchase price, the buyer may not be able to borrow enough to complete the transaction at the contracted price. This is not common, but it is more likely in suburbs where there is limited recent sales data or where prices have moved quickly.</p>

      <p>There is also the question of the property itself. Lenders apply their own criteria to the properties they will lend against. A property with structural issues, certain types of construction, or a strata building with outstanding levies may not meet a specific lender's requirements, even if the borrower's financial position is strong.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How finance conditions work in a Queensland contract</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, residential property contracts typically include a finance condition that gives the buyer a set period, usually 14 to 21 days, to obtain formal approval. If the buyer cannot obtain finance within that period, they can terminate the contract and recover their deposit. If the buyer allows the finance condition to lapse without notifying the seller, the contract generally becomes unconditional and the buyer takes on the risk of completing without finance.</p>

      <p>As a seller, you will occasionally receive a request for a finance extension. This happens when the buyer's lender needs more time to complete the valuation or assessment. Extensions are common and are not necessarily a sign of a problem. A request for a short extension of three to five business days while a valuation is being processed is routine. A request for a second or third extension, or a very long extension, warrants more careful consideration.</p>

      <p>Whether to grant an extension depends on your circumstances and your alternatives. If you have no other interested buyers and granting a short extension keeps a good offer on the table, it usually makes sense to agree. If you are in a position where you could relaunch the property and attract competing offers, you have more leverage to assess the situation carefully before agreeing. Your agent should be able to advise you on whether the buyer's situation appears to be progressing normally or whether there are signals that the approval is in genuine difficulty.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens when finance falls over after exchange</h2>
      <p>If a buyer cannot obtain finance within the finance condition period and terminates the contract, they are entitled to recover their deposit and neither party has a claim against the other. The seller returns to the market.</p>

      <p>If a buyer allows the finance condition to lapse and the contract becomes unconditional, but they subsequently cannot complete, the situation is more serious. The seller can retain the deposit and may have grounds to pursue the buyer for any loss suffered, including the cost of relaunching the property and any shortfall if it ultimately sells for less. In practice, most sellers in this situation focus on securing their next sale rather than pursuing litigation, but the legal position is substantially different from a termination during the finance condition period.</p>

      <p>This is why unconditional offers are valued by sellers. A buyer who makes an unconditional offer has accepted the risk that they must complete regardless of what happens with their finance. Cash buyers are unconditional by definition. Buyers with formal approval already in hand may also be willing to go unconditional or to accept a shorter finance condition period, which reduces the seller's exposure and can justify accepting a slightly lower price.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Managing conditional offers with confidence</h2>
      <p>The practical implication for sellers is this: pre-approval is a positive signal but not a guarantee. The most useful question to ask, through your agent, is whether the buyer has spoken to their lender about the specific property and whether there are any known concerns. A buyer whose broker has already flagged potential valuation risk or a strata levy issue is in a different position from one whose lender has indicated the property is a straightforward assessment.</p>

      <p>It is also worth understanding the buyer's deposit situation. A buyer with a large deposit relative to the purchase price has more buffer if a valuation comes in slightly short, because they can make up the difference without requiring additional borrowing. A buyer with a 5% deposit has much less room to move if the bank values the property below the agreed price.</p>

      <p>None of this means you should avoid accepting offers with finance conditions. The vast majority of Queensland residential transactions include a finance condition and settle without issue. What it does mean is that understanding the buyer's position helps you negotiate from a position of knowledge rather than assumption, and makes it easier to respond appropriately if something does not go to plan.</p>

